{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594425"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15311"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15311"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.18,0.04,0.07,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8002"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8002"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51286"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"8760"},{"type":"tags","id":"10095"},{"type":"tags","id":"10145"},{"type":"tags","id":"10146"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGallstone disease is a common condition affecting the biliary system. Multiple risk factors have been identified that increase the likelihood of developing gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a risk factor for gallstone formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["African descent","Asian descent","Being underweight","Male sex","Pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe risk factors for gallstones are commonly and rather casually remembered as the \u00275 F\u0027s\u0027: Fair, Fat, Female, Fecund and Forty. The \u0027Fair\u0027 refers to white skin, with the observation that gallstone disease appears to be more common in caucasian populations. \u003Cstrong\u003EAfrican descent\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor for gallstones; gallstones are less common in African populations compared to European populations. \u003Cstrong\u003EAsian descent\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with a different pattern of gallstone disease but is not a major risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeing \u003Cstrong\u003Eunderweight\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor; obesity increases gallstone risk. With the global increase in the prevalence of obesity, it is now well documented that \u0027Fat\u0027 is an important risk factor for many other conditions apart from gallstones. Certainly gallstones are seen more often in \u0027Females\u0027 rather than the \u003Cstrong\u003EMale sex\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u0027Fecundity\u0027 is a significant risk factor for gallstone formation. During pregnancy, elevated oestrogen levels increase cholesterol secretion into bile, while progesterone reduces gallbladder motility. These hormonal changes create an environment that promotes gallstone formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertainly the prevalence of gallstones increases with age and being over \u0027Forty.\u0027 It is estimated that in caucasian communities some 20% of individuals over 40 years and 30% of those over 70 years of age will develop gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Risk factors for gallstones include female sex, fertility, forty-plus age, fat body habitus, and fair background (5 F\u0027s).","Pregnancy increases risk of gallstone formation due to elevated oestrogen levels and altered bile composition."],"references":["Dave HD, Shumway KR, Al Obaidi NM. Physiology, Biliary. [Updated 2022 Dec 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537107/","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Lammert F, Gurusamy K, Ko CW, Miquel JF, M\u00e9ndez-S\u00e1nchez N, Portincasa P, van Erpecum KJ, van Laarhoven CJ, Wang DQ. Gallstones. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Apr 28;2:16024. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.24. PMID: 27121416"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51286"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15311"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51286"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T09:28:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T09:28:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8002"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65841"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":nu